[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":460},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2021\u002F10\u002F27\u002Fnpm-ci-vs-npm-install-differences\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2021\u002F10\u002F27\u002Fnpm-ci-vs-npm-install-differences\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2021\u002F10\u002F27\u002Fnpm-ci-vs-npm-install-differences\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2021\u002F10\u002F27\u002Fnpm-ci-vs-npm-install-differences\u002F":435,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2021\u002F10\u002F27\u002Fnpm-ci-vs-npm-install-differences\u002F":444},"\u002Fnodejs\u002F20211027\u002F1827968017\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":416,"date":417,"description":418,"extension":419,"lang":420,"meta":421,"navigation":422,"path":423,"readingMinutes":424,"seo":425,"standalone":426,"stem":427,"tags":428,"tldr":431,"updated":432,"url":433,"__hash__":434},"content\u002Fen\u002FNodejs\u002Fnpm-ci-vs-npm-install-differences.md","npm ci vs npm install: What's the Difference?","7176819812",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":407},"minimark",[11,35,40,49,53,64,87,96,100,106,116,122,132,141,153,165,172,182,200,215,221,227,239,278,289,294,299,304,309,320,324,344,347,363,372,381,385],[12,13,16],"callout",{"title":14,"type":15},"Note","note",[17,18,19,23,24,27,28,23,31,34],"p",{},[20,21,22],"code",{},"npm ci"," restores from ",[20,25,26],{},"package-lock.json"," with versions locked — good for CI\u002FCD and team restores. ",[20,29,30],{},"npm install",[20,32,33],{},"package.json"," and can quietly bump versions — good for adding or updating dependencies during dev.",[36,37,39],"h2",{"id":38},"intro","Intro",[17,41,42,43,45,46,48],{},"Most of us are used to running ",[20,44,30],{}," to restore a project, but since npm 5.7.1 a lot of folks recommend ",[20,47,22],{}," instead. Let's go through why.",[36,50,52],{"id":51},"what-is-npm-ci","What is npm ci?",[17,54,55,56,58,59,63],{},"The \"ci\" in ",[20,57,22],{}," stands for ",[60,61,62],"strong",{},"Continuous Integration",". It was introduced in npm 5.7.1, so if your npm is older than that, you can't use this command.",[17,65,66,67,69,70,73,74,76,77,79,80,82,83,86],{},"It's similar to ",[20,68,30],{}," (and ",[20,71,72],{},"npm i","). Officially ",[20,75,22],{}," is supposed to install faster than ",[20,78,30],{},", but in my own tests ",[20,81,30],{}," was actually faster. From what I've read in discussions, that's usually because ",[20,84,85],{},"node_modules"," is cached.",[17,88,89,90,92,93,95],{},"So what's the actual difference between ",[20,91,22],{}," and ",[20,94,30],{},"? Let's keep going.",[36,97,99],{"id":98},"npm-install-vs-npm-ci","npm install vs npm ci",[17,101,102,103,105],{},"First, ",[20,104,30],{},". You'd typically use it in two situations:",[107,108,109,113],"ul",{},[110,111,112],"li",{},"Installing a specific package",[110,114,115],{},"Restoring a project",[17,117,118,119,121],{},"When ",[20,120,30],{}," finishes, you usually see two things appear:",[107,123,124,128],{},[110,125,126],{},[20,127,85],{},[110,129,130],{},[20,131,26],{},[17,133,134,135,137,138,140],{},"We can skip ",[20,136,85],{}," — that's just where packages live. The interesting one is ",[20,139,26],{},".",[17,142,143,145,146,148,149,152],{},[20,144,26],{}," looks a bit like the ",[20,147,33],{}," that ",[20,150,151],{},"npm init"," generates, except it records dependency versions in painful detail. It was introduced in npm 5, and its job is to lock the exact dependency versions an install produced.",[17,154,155,156,92,158,160,161,164],{},"If you actually open ",[20,157,33],{},[20,159,26],{}," side by side, you'll see how much more detailed the lock file is. Here's ",[20,162,163],{},"axios"," as an example:",[17,166,167],{},[168,169],"img",{"alt":170,"src":171},"package-lock.json vs package.json","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FAZcXwUx.png",[17,173,174,175,177,178,181],{},"It even records what ",[20,176,163],{}," depends on (like ",[20,179,180],{},"follow-redirects",").",[17,183,184,185,187,188,197,198,140],{},"So why am I making a big deal of ",[20,186,26],{},"? Because ",[60,189,190,23,192,194,195],{},[20,191,22],{},[20,193,26],{},", not from ",[20,196,33],{}," — that's the key difference from ",[20,199,30],{},[17,201,202,203,205,206,208,209,211,212,214],{},"What's the benefit of restoring with ",[20,204,22],{},"? The short version is: ",[20,207,22],{}," is built for CI\u002FCD and test environments. But why is it recommended for restoring dev environments too? You've probably hit this — when you take over a project and run ",[20,210,30],{},", npm quietly updates some things, and ",[20,213,26],{}," ends up modified for no obvious reason. If you've got version control turned on, it shows up like this:",[17,216,217],{},[168,218],{"alt":219,"src":220},"Files quietly updated","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FzQr0rnn.png",[17,222,223,224,226],{},"(Side note: yes, you should commit ",[20,225,26],{}," to version control.)",[17,228,229,230,232,233,235,236,238],{},"These silent updates can lead to package version incompatibilities and other \"why is this broken?\" debugging sessions. That's where ",[20,231,22],{}," helps — since it installs from ",[20,234,26],{},", the versions are exactly what the lock file says, no surprise updates. A few things to be aware of when using ",[20,237,22],{},":",[107,240,241,251,256,262,270],{},[110,242,243,244,246,247,250],{},"You must have a ",[20,245,26],{}," or ",[20,248,249],{},"npm-shrinkwrap.json"," (another lockfile, less common).",[110,252,253,255],{},[20,254,22],{}," can only restore the entire dependency tree at once — you can't install one package with it (which you probably wouldn't want anyway).",[110,257,258,259,261],{},"If ",[20,260,85],{}," already exists, it deletes the folder first and then installs.",[110,263,264,265,267,268,140],{},"If a dependency error occurs during install, ",[20,266,22],{}," exits instead of touching ",[20,269,33],{},[110,271,272,274,275,277],{},[20,273,22],{}," never modifies ",[20,276,33],{},", so versions stay locked.",[17,279,280,282,283,288],{},[20,281,22],{}," sounds great for restores. The official line is that ",[60,284,285,286],{},"it's faster than ",[20,287,30],{},", and here's a comparison:",[17,290,291,293],{},[20,292,30],{}," took 16 seconds:",[17,295,296],{},[168,297],{"alt":30,"src":298},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FJRRkYB7.png",[17,300,301,303],{},[20,302,22],{}," took 14 seconds:",[17,305,306],{},[168,307],{"alt":22,"src":308},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FPhYUyf7.png",[17,310,311,312,319],{},"Honestly, I think they're basically the same — see the ",[313,314,318],"a",{"href":315,"rel":316},"https:\u002F\u002Fdocs.npmjs.com\u002Fcli\u002Fv6\u002Fcommands\u002Fnpm-ci",[317],"nofollow","official docs"," for more on this.",[36,321,323],{"id":322},"so-which-should-i-use-npm-install-or-npm-ci","So which should I use — npm install or npm ci?",[17,325,326,327,331,332,334,335,337,338,340,341,343],{},"Both have their place. When you want to restore ",[328,329,330],"em",{},"and"," update packages, use ",[20,333,30],{},". When you want exact versions and don't want to touch ",[20,336,26],{},", use ",[20,339,22],{},". And for CI\u002FCD, ",[20,342,22],{}," is the better, more reliable choice.",[17,345,346],{},"There's a lot of reading on this if you want to go deeper:",[107,348,349,356],{},[110,350,351],{},[313,352,355],{"href":353,"rel":354},"https:\u002F\u002Fbetterprogramming.pub\u002Fnpm-ci-vs-npm-install-which-should-you-use-in-your-node-js-projects-51e07cb71e26",[317],"npm ci vs. npm install — Which Should You Use in Your Node.js Projects?",[110,357,358],{},[313,359,362],{"href":360,"rel":361},"https:\u002F\u002Fstackoverflow.com\u002Fquestions\u002F52499617\u002Fwhat-is-the-difference-between-npm-install-and-npm-ci",[317],"What is the difference between \"npm install\" and \"npm ci\"?",[17,364,365,366,368,369,371],{},"Some folks even argue you should always use ",[20,367,22],{}," instead of ",[20,370,30],{}," for restores:",[107,373,374],{},[110,375,376],{},[313,377,380],{"href":378,"rel":379},"https:\u002F\u002Fstackoverflow.com\u002Fquestions\u002F53469032\u002Fusing-npm-ci-instead-of-npm-install-for-deterministic-project-setup",[317],"Using \"npm ci\" instead of \"npm install\" for deterministic project setup",[36,382,384],{"id":383},"references","References",[107,386,387,392,397,402],{},[110,388,389],{},[313,390,22],{"href":315,"rel":391},[317],[110,393,394],{},[313,395,355],{"href":353,"rel":396},[317],[110,398,399],{},[313,400,362],{"href":360,"rel":401},[317],[110,403,404],{},[313,405,380],{"href":378,"rel":406},[317],{"title":408,"searchDepth":409,"depth":409,"links":410},"",2,[411,412,413,414,415],{"id":38,"depth":409,"text":39},{"id":51,"depth":409,"text":52},{"id":98,"depth":409,"text":99},{"id":322,"depth":409,"text":323},{"id":383,"depth":409,"text":384},"Nodejs","2021-10-27 21:24:14","Most of us are used to running `npm install` when restoring a project, but since npm 5.7.1 there's been a recommendation to use `npm ci` instead. This post walks through why, and when each one is the right call.","md","en",{},true,"\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002Fnpm-ci-vs-npm-install-differences","4",{"title":6,"description":418},false,"en\u002FNodejs\u002Fnpm-ci-vs-npm-install-differences",[429,430],"npm","Node.js",null,"2026-05-12 09:00:00","\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2021\u002F10\u002F27\u002Fnpm-ci-vs-npm-install-differences\u002F","n_WGBGX4ICdoIDOhDaKuG7i9qEYv_y024ptSwV7LTiE",{"newer":436,"older":440},{"url":437,"title":438,"date":439},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2021\u002F10\u002F29\u002Fforeach-async-await-problem\u002F","Why Does async\u002Fawait Quietly Break Inside forEach? (And How to Fix It)","2021-10-29 21:38:47",{"url":441,"title":442,"date":443},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2021\u002F10\u002F24\u002Fjavascript-core-68-es6-arrow-functions-exercise\u002F","JavaScript Core Concepts (68) - ES6 Arrow Functions: Chapter Exercise","2021-10-24 16:57:45",[445,450,455],{"url":446,"title":447,"date":448,"readingMinutes":449},"\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2026\u002F01\u002F13\u002Frun-multiple-commands-with-concurrently\u002F","Tired of Opening Multiple Terminals to Run Commands? Use Concurrently","2026-01-13 09:45:28","2",{"url":451,"title":452,"date":453,"readingMinutes":454},"\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2025\u002F03\u002F13\u002Fhexschool-ecommerce-api-complete-tutorial\u002F","Hexschool Capstone Class Study Group: Complete E-commerce API Tutorial","2025-03-13 09:13:26","9",{"url":456,"title":457,"date":458,"readingMinutes":459},"\u002Fen\u002Fnodejs\u002F2024\u002F12\u002F25\u002Fpm2-process-manager-not-pm25\u002F","PM2 Is Process Manager, Not PM2.5","2024-12-25 10:31:33","5",1784087336894]